<HEADLINE> Catholic Young Man Murdered Near Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A Roman Catholic man in his early
20s was found murdered in Northern Ireland Saturday, the second
victim of sectarian violence in the province since the historic
peace accord was struck on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland police said the body of the victim with
bullets wounds in his head was found near a railway station in the
county of Antrim north of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The body was found by a taxi driver on a road close to the
railway station in Crumlin village early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC, two men were being questioned over the
murder of the young man.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened only one day after two key Protestant
guerrilla groups, the Ulster Defense Association and Ulster
Freedom Fighters, announced their support for the Northern Ireland
peace deal reached by eight main Protestant and Catholic political
parties and the British and Irish governments.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a 29-year-old Catholic was shot dead by a suspected
pro-British "loyalist" guerrillas in the town of Portadown, 40 km
south of Belfast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
