<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Calls for Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa Saturday called on Zimbabweans to keep striving for
economic independence, after having won political independence
from British colonialists in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Addressing thousands of people at the Great Zimbabwe Monument
near Masvingo, over 300 km south of Harare, Mkapa noted that the
struggle for such independence would be won in the end, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We won the war of liberation but the struggle continues for
economic emancipation," said Mkapa at the rally, which marked the
last official engagement of his four-day state visit to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
However, Mkapa warned the Zimbabweans to watch
out against some "adversaries" in the struggle for economic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
"They stood by during the struggle for liberation. Now they
are very free with their advice. They were very mean when we
were fighting. Now they are free with advice about what
constitutes democracy. They want to teach us about the meaning
of dictatorship," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent reference to Zimbabwe's last colonial ruler
Ian Smith, Mkapa said, just as "some people" had said blacks
would not rule this country for a long time, they also thought
black economic empowerment might never be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mkapa wound up his visit with a news conference at
Harare International Airport where he called for strengthening of
economic and political relations between Zimbabwe and his
country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said the visit by the
Tanzanian president had solidified relations between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
