<HEADLINE> 2 Nigerian Tourists Wounded in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Two Nigerian tourists who tried to
pass Turkish-Syrian border without permission were shot and
wounded by Turkish security forces in southeastern Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened in Gaziantep province linking neighboring
Syria when the Turkish security forces opened fire on four
Nigerian tourists as they tried to enter Turkey from Syria and
ignored the Turkish security forces' call for them to stop,
according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Two of the Nigerian tourists are women. The wounded tourists,
Revin Adan and Cathrine Oanen, were immediately hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
The news agency added that the other two in the group, Kemo
Saidy and Bright Owagne, surrendered to the Turkish security
forces.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are underway against the Nigerian tourists who
intended to enter Turkey through illegal ways although they had
passports, said the news agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
