<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean War Veterans Demand Posts in Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The national executive of the
Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans Association (ZNLWVA)
Saturday resolved to hold congress from May 8 to 10 with demands
for a quota of positions in the cabinet high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
They also demand positions in the ruling Zimbabwe Africa
National Union Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) politburo, parliament
and the diplomatic service, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
ZNLWVA National Chairman Chenjerai Hunzvi, whose entire
executive will be seeking re-election, said the congress will be
held at Umzingwane High School at Esigodini in Matabeleland South
Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Hunzvi, the ZNLWVA was seeking quotas in the
various sectors of the public service to enable the "liberators"
to participate in all spheres of the government.
</P>
<P>
"This will mean that we will be able to participate in all
functions and matters of the state," he said without giving
specific figures for the number of posts the war veterans want in
each sector.
</P>
<P>
The ZNLWVA will also seek to strengthen its financial position
through mobilizing funds from among the veterans' recently paid
back-dated pensions by the state in recognition of their role in
the war that ended with Zimbabwe's independence in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
