<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Greek General Heads Cyprus Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Greek Lieutenant General Dimitris
Demou became the new Commander of Cyprus' National Guard Saturday,
replaying his compatriot predecessor.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony at the army's headquarters here, he formally
replaced Lieutenant General Nicolaos Vorvolakos who headed the
10,000-strong Cypriot troops in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
The replacement came in the framework of a 1993 joint defense
agreement between Athens and Nicosia, under which Greece will
provide military assistance to the island country in case it is
attacked.
</P>
<P>
At present, many officers in Cyprus' National Guard are from
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
Mediterranean island after a pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained about 40,000-strong troops in northern
Cyprus, which was declared by Turkish Cypriots in 1983 as a
breakaway republic, but recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
