<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Gas Loses 20,000 Customers A Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 20,000 domestic gas customers
a day are switching suppliers since the introduction of
competition in the domestic gas market two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.5 million homes, or about 19 percent of the domestic
market, have either switched or agreed to switch suppliers,
according to figures released Saturday by Ofgas, the industry
regulator.
</P>
<P>
People were switching because alternative suppliers were
offering savings of up to 70 pounds (112 U.S. dollars) a year on
the average bill, said Clare Spottiswoode, director general of
Ofgas.
</P>
<P>
The large number of people moving suppliers showed that
"Britain has the biggest most competitive gas market in the
world," the regulator said.
</P>
<P>
Some 13 million homes, about three quarters of all domestic
customers, were now able to move to a new supplier, it added.
</P>
<P>
The final phase of domestic competition will be triggered next
month when 5.2 million customers in London and East Anglia will be
able to choose another gas supplier, according to Ofgas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
