<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Under an agreement signed Saturday, Spain will provide
Jordan with 6.38 million U.S. dollars of technical aid in the
period of 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be used for projects in the fields of culture,
education, science, health and agriculture, Jordan's official news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here as the joint Jordanian-Spanish
committee concluded its two-day meeting on bilateral cooperation
in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- The Suez Canal Authority of Egypt is currently
deepening the southern sector of shipping course of the canal in
order to bring its depth to 62 feet (19 meters) by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Fattah Al-Mikati, director of the Suez Canal Dredgers
Department, announced Friday that the authority is carrying out
the current deepening operations with its own potentials without
outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- The Arab gross national product (GNP) for 1997
amounted to 600 billion U.S. dollars, or 500 million dollars more
than that of the previous year, a latest Arab League report said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab exports volume in 1997 were estimated at 41.5 billion
dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that most Arab countries succeeded in
controlling their inflation rates below 10.4 percent last year,
compared with 12.9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Arab foreign debts in 1997 accounted for 32.9 percent of the
Arab gross domestic product (GDP), compared with 35.7 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and France have signed a Financial Cooperation
Protocol here to give Ankara a loan of 100 million French francs
(16.4 million U.S. dollars) for two projects, local newspapers
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, 87 percent of the loan will be used to
finance the Water Purification Plant Project in Erzurum near
Iran. The rest of the loan will go to the Anatolian University
Civil Aviation High School Research and Development Project.
</P>
</TEXT>
