<HEADLINE> Syria Reiterates Opposition to Israeli Conditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Syrian First Vice President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam Saturday reiterated Damascus' rejection to the
Israeli offer of conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon,
terming its as "a violation" of U.N. Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival here Saturday afternoon for a visit,
Khaddam said that through the plan, Israel is trying to get out of
the dilemma it has created by its aggressive and expansionist
policies, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet decided on April 1 to accept the resolution
which called for unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon, but demands negotiated security arrangements by the
Lebanese government that would protect its northern towns from
Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam said that the conditions set forth by Israel for
implementation of the resolution violate the resolution.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Palestinian peace track, he termed as "corrupt"
the forthcoming separate talks between the U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu in London on May 4.
</P>
<P>
"Such negotiations can only benefit the aggressor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Receiving his Syrian counterpart at the airport, Iranian First
Vice President Hassan Habibi also voiced Tehran's opposition to
the Israeli offer of conditional withdrawal from Lebanon, saying
that "such conditions are not reasonable and certainly not
supported by Iran."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated Iran's objection to the Turkish military
cooperation with Israel, adding that the issue would be discussed
in meetings between officials of Iran and Syria during Khaddam's
stay here.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have signed two military cooperation
agreements, arousing criticism from Arab countries who fear that
Turkey is allying itself against Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to bilateral relations, Habibi said that regular
meetings of Iranian-Syrian joint committee are indicative of the
two countries' resolve to consult on various issues.
</P>
<P>
Besides holding talks with Iranian leaders and officials,
Khaddam will also take part in meetings of the joint committee,
which meets every six months in either of the two capitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
