<HEADLINE> Kuwait Plans Work-at-Home Employment System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti will hold an
international conference next month to discuss ways enabling over
87,000 qualified but unemployed Kuwaiti women to work from home.
</P>
<P>
Women's Committee of the Social Reform Society Chairwoman Saud
Al-Jarallah told reporters here Saturday that the meeting due to be
held from May 4 to 6 will discuss bringing new ideas like an
"office at home" to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"This will open up opportunities for women to work from home in
about 46 occupations," she added.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jarallah said that during the last two years, over 4,300
working women, including 1,600 university graduates, were forced
to retire from different jobs because of social commitments.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will host specialists from Malaysia, Sweden,
Britain and many Arab and African countries, Al-Jarallah said.
</P>
<P>
According to latest official statistics, only 60,000 women out
of 147,115 women in Kuwait who hold educational qualifications,
including 23,446 university graduates, have jobs.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, there are over 87,000 educated women,
including 2,367 university graduates, are not working due to
domestic and social commitments. Female population currently
account for 50.4 percent of the 710,000 citizens in the Gulf
state.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on the needs of the Kuwaiti labor
market with a view to absorbing women into it, Al-Jarallah said.
</P>
<P>
She said she believes the "office at home" system will enable
the women to have new access to the labor market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
