<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Disappointed With Substandard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
disappointed with the mushrooming of substandard and unregistered
preschools and day care centers in the country, Lusaka Province
Minister Sony Mulenga said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga insisted that all the preschools and day care centers
owners must comply with the law because most centers are
operating contrary to the Nurseries Act.
</P>
<P>
When officiating the Zambia preschool annual general meeting
at the University of Zambia, Mulenga appealed to the preschool
owners to review their fees which he described as "unrealistic".
</P>
<P>
Currently, he said, only a few children can go to such schools
because of the unrealistic fees.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Preschool Association President Emmanuel Chisenga urged
the government to consider allocating them a place and a vehicle
to enable the association to reach out to all corners of the
country.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, professor Mutale Chanda, acting
vice-chancellor of the university, pledged continued support to
the Zambia Preschool Association.
</P>
<P>
Chanda said the university will soon introduce a degree
program in early childhood education because it acknowledges the
importance of early child education in the development of a
child.
</P>
<P>
The university has embarked on a number of workshops for
preschool proprietors and administrators to educate them on
various issues concerning early child education, said Chanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
