<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Its Role in Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Personal envoy of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Deputy Foreign Minister Viktor
Posuvalyuk said here Saturday that his country is preparing for
pushing forward the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Russia will send a senior official to the Middle East in May
for talks with regional leaders on the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Posuvalyuk said that Russia, as a
permanent member in the U.N. Security Council, will play its role
in the affairs of the region.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk arrived here on Saturday morning from Uganda's
capital Kampala for a short visit to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He has met Sudanese President Omar Al-Bashir and First Vice
President Ali Osman Mohammed Taha and held talks with Foreign
Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail on Sudan's ties with other countries
as well as ways of developing relations between Sudan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
He exchanged views with Sudanese leaders on some regional and
international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official noted that his visits to Kampala and
Khartoum are part of Russian mediation efforts to solve the
dispute between Uganda and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbor countries have been exchanging accusations of
interfering in each other's internal affairs. The diplomatic ties
between them were severed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk ruled out the existence of any ideological links
between his country and the Sudanese rebel movement operating in
south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Sudanese government and the
rebel movement People's Liberation Army would be able to reach a
peaceful solution of the question of south Sudan through the
upcoming peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Rebels have been fighting against the Islamic government in
Sudan since 1983 to press for increased autonomy for the southern
third of Sudan, which is mainly African, Christian and Animist.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk ended his visit here and left on Saturday evening.
</P>
