<HEADLINE> Low Turnout Marks Nigeria's Parliament Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's national assembly
election Saturday was marked by a very low turnout, amid a calm
and peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
At several polling stations in Lagos State where Xinhua
correspondents visited, it is estimated that less than 20 percent
of the registered voters had cast their votes by 2:30 P.M., half
an hour before the end of the polls.
</P>
<P>
In a polling station on the Ikoyi Island where about 300
voters were registered, only less than 20 votes were seen in the
transparent ballot by the closure time.
</P>
<P>
The vote started around 8:00 a.m. at about 1,114 polling
stations nationwide and ended at around 3:00 p.m.. There is no
reports of violence so far.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election are expected to produce 109 senators and
360 members of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The national assembly election is a major part of the
transition to civil rule in accordance with a civil rule program
announced in 1995 by the military government of General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Grassroots Democratic Movement (GDM)
joined Nigeria's four other political parties to adopt General
Abacha as their sole candidate for the presidential elections
scheduled for August 1.
</P>
<P>
Many Nigerians have expressed their disappointment over the
parties and, indeed, to the transition program, while opposition
groups have called for a boycott of Saturday's election and all
subsequent elections under the transition program.
</P>
<P>
At a polling station on the Lagos Island, a GDM agent
monitoring the election said many people simply chose to stay
home even if the persons of parties and electoral agencies were
going from house to house trying to peruade them to come out and
vote.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
