<HEADLINE> EU Pledges Continued Support for Zambian Artists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) pledged
here Saturday to continue supporting Zambian artists to exploit
their full potential so that they can compete favorably with
their counterparts across the world.
</P>
<P>
Charles Brook, EU representative in Zambia, said at an
exhibition of paintings and sculpture to mark
the Europe Day, which falls Saturday, that there are so many
Zambians talented in the arts who need support.
</P>
<P>
Brook said over the years EU has spent over 1.8 billion Kwacha
(about one million U.S. Dollars) to promote the arts of Zambia
and it will continue to support arts-oriented programs
such as rock painting, sculpturing and existing museums in the
country.
</P>
<P>
EU will continue to support the expansion of the Livingstone
and Lusaka national museums which have very important
collections, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mumba Kapumpa, Chairman of the Zambia Arts Council, bemoaned
the lack of interest by Zambians in promoting the arts.
</P>
<P>
"We need more and more Zambians to appreciate arts. I am sad
to see that the people patronizing the exhibition are foreigners
but there are very few Zambians. It should be the other way
round," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kapumpa called on the government to support the arts by
waiving import duty on tools of trade such as brushes and paint
so that many talented people can buy the tools and contribute to
the trade in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
