<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross, Netanyahu Discuss Size of Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- United States peace envoy
Dennis Ross began his new shuttle mission here late Saturday with
discussions with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the
second Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross, accompanied by Assistant Secretary of State for Near
Eastern Affairs and former U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk,
held the meeting with Netanyahu at the Prime Minister's Office
shortly after his arrival here.
</P>
<P>
No details were disclosed about the meeting, but top on Ross'
agenda was to persuade Netanyahu to accept the U.S. proposal for a
13.1 percent Israeli redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Ross' latest mission is aimed at breaking the year-old
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process by defining the
size of the second redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
As Netanyahu and Ross were talking, dozens of activists from
the peace movement Peace Now held a protest outside the Prime
Minister's Office to protest against Netanyahu's policy, saying it
is destroying the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Several protesters held a huge cartoon which depicted Netanyahu
as strangling with his hands a pigeon, the symbol of peace.
</P>
<P>
Trying to solve the dispute over the size of Israeli further
redeployment, Ross will set the stage for the four-way talks in
London to be co-hosted on May 4 by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. The London
talks were the result of Blair's visit to the region earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
Before departing for the region, Ross met in New York with
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan to hold consultation
on the new U.S. initiative.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Netanyahu, Ross is to hold talks with
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, who
said in Gaza Saturday that he hoped the Americans to push Israel
to accept the U.S. initiative. As a compromise, the PNA has
already endorsed the U.S. proposal for a 13.1 percent
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
However, even before Ross began his mission here, the
U.S. downplayed expectation for a dramatic breakthrough from Ross'
new round of diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
State Department Spokesman James Rubin said Friday that it was
hard to be optimistic about the latest U.S. mediation because
there was no reason to know that Ross' mission would yield
anything but the kind of refusal to make hard decisions as seen in
the past.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier report Saturday, the state-run Israel Radio
quoted Israeli officials as saying that Netanyahu would refuse
again to accept the U.S. proposal because his Cabinet had
rejected any redeployment more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
But some other reports have said that Netanyahu might accept a
redeployment of 11 percent in order to pressure the Palestinian
side to intensify its fight against terrorism and enter the
long-overdue final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is to convene on Sunday a meeting of the Inner
Cabinet to discuss Ross' mission and coordinate Israel's
position. Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said the inner cabinet was to deliberate a
demand for creating an American-Israeli-Palestinian committee to
decide on the size of the second redeployment and its effects
on the final-status talks, as well as the time table for the
PNA to implement its security promises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
