<HEADLINE> Moya Takes Monte Carlo Open Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Spain's Carlos Moya on Sunday beat
Frenchman Cedric Pioline in straight sets to win the 2.2 million
U.S. dollar Monte Carlo Open.
</P>
<P>
Moya, 1997 Australian Open losing finalist, won the one-sided
match 6-3, 6-0, 7-5 in just under two hours.
</P>
<P>
The seeded 14th had an impressive week in Monte Carlo with wins
over Austrian Thomas Muster and former Wimbledon champion Richard
Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
His final against Pioline was arguably his easiest contest,
even if the Frenchman fought hard in the third set.
</P>
<P>
Pioline looked exhausted after his tense semifinal against
another Spaniard, Alberto Berasategui, in which he saved two match
points before fighting his way back from 6-4, 0-6, 1-5 down to win.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman may also have suffered again from his finals jinx
-- he has now lost 12 of the 14 finals he has played, including
Wimbledon last year and the U.S. Open in 1993. 
</P>
