<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq said on Sunday that a Russian proposal at the
United Nations to end inspections of suspected Iraqi nuclear sites
fell far short of what Iraq deserved.
</P>
<P>
Humam Abdul Khaliq, minister of information and culture, was
quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency as saying that the
Russian-suggested change from inspections to a monitoring phase
"does not represent Iraq's minimal due."
</P>
<P>
The Russian proposal "addresses a partial situation," and "if
this is all the U.N. Security Council's April discussions would
lead to," it does not meet Iraq's expectations, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Russia floated a draft resolution calling for an end
to inspections of Iraq's suspected nuclear sites because there was
no proof that Iraq is still working on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Khaliq said this resolution "would serve the American tactics
intended to derail the course of discussions from their core and
gain time to prolong the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that all proscribed weapons under U.N. resolution
687, and their related facilities and equipment, have been
dismantled since late 1991. (Iraq-Russian Proposal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban and the rival
Northern Alliance have agreed to end their current peace talks in
Islamabad in three to five days, a senior U.N. official said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides decided to work very hard to finish their work
within three consecutive days if possible but not later than five
days," said James Ngobi, Head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said the Joint Steering Committee, which is made up of
five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, spent their first
session discussing the procedures and reached agreement on a
number of procedures.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were now engaged in working on the provisional
agenda, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official, who is presiding over the intra-Afghan
talks, said the Taliban and the alliance agreed that the United
Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
should be designated as the co-chairmen of the meeting.
(Afghanistan-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A high ranking agent of the British Intelligence
Service (MI6) has been arrested in Iran under charges of illegally
filming military areas.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gavin was detained in Iran's western province of
Kurdistan while taking pictures and shooting films of military
establishments, Iran's morning daily Jomhuri Islami Sunday quoted
an informed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed source said that Gavin, holding a tourist visa,
entered the military areas without any permission as a reporter of
the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).
</P>
<P>
The MI6 agent has been in detention for a week for questioning
and he has confessed to his spying activities in Iran and several
Arab countries, the source said. However, no Iranian authorities
have confirmed the arrest.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab diplomats and reporters here described Gavin's
activities as "suspicious," saying that BBC has screened several
films made by the Briton from prohibited and sensitive military
areas in Arab countries. (Iran-UK-Spy) 
</P>
