<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Speaker: Israel Must Implement Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel must carry out its third
phase troop redeployment in the West Bank under the signed
Oslo Accords, Speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC)
Abu Ala said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Ala told 12 representatives from the European Union to
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) at the PNA Education
Ministry in Ramallah that Israeli troop redeployment was
stipulated in the Oslo Accords and Israel had to implement it.
</P>
<P>
Abu Ala's remarks were apparently PNA's response to Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's statement Saturday that
he would tell U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross that unless the size
of a third redeployment is set, Israel would not agree to a
second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S.-brokered Hebron agreement in January 1997,
Netanyahu promised to redeploy its troops in the West Bank in
three stages by this summer.
</P>
<P>
Israel has also said that it would not accept the second stage
troop redeployment in the West Bank until the PNA agreed to move
onto the final-status peace talks.
</P>
<P>
According to accords between Israel and Palestine, the two
sides will settle the thorniest issues of Jerusalem, final borders
and Palestinian refugees in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank is one of the key
issues that hinders the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. has raised an initiative, which is under discussion
between Netanyahu and Ross, asking Israel to hand over a further
13.1 percent of the West Bank to the PNA over 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israel has refused to accept the initiative though it has
soften its position and is willing to offer a pullback of 11
percent up from the earlier limit of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here Saturday to conduct his current shuttle
diplomacy between Israel and the PNA. He started his second round
of talks here Sunday afternoon with Netanyahu and was scheduled
to meet PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat late in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Ross's main mission this time is to lay the ground work for the
London talks, which are aimed at ending the current crisis over
Israeli troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
As arranged by British Prime Minister Tony Blair, U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet separately in
London on May 4 with Arafat and Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
