<HEADLINE> Somali Clan Fighting Kills 40 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 26 (Xinhua) -- After six relatively good
years, a major clan animosity seems to be reigniting once again
among the two large communities of Darod and Hawiye.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of hostility emerged after the two sub-clans
of Majerten and Marehan had re-energized their fight for control
of the Southern port town of Kismayu in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
A large offensive campaign launched by the Majerten sub-clan
against the Marehan militiamen outside Kismayu has resulted in
killing more than 40 people and wounded over 60 others in the
past three days.
</P>
<P>
Also in this period, the Majerten militiamen have gained
control of more than 100 km territory covering the villages of
Gobwein, Yontoy, Bulo Gudud and others earlier controlled by
Marehan militiamen.
</P>
<P>
According to reports received here through the VHF radios, the
fighting was in its highest peak Saturday after the Marehan
militiamen were driven back toward the defensive positions of the
Hawiye militiamen near Kansuma village which is where the equator
passes through in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
During the fighting, the Majerten militiamen led by the
son-in-law of Somalia's late dictator, General Mohamed Said Hirsi
Morgan, have also captured 20 prisoners who were all taken back
to the town of Kismayu, 500 Km South of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The fighting has then spread to territories controlled by
Hussein Aidid's faction in Lower Jubba region.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the captured prisoners also include
four militiamen from the Habar Gidir clan of Hussein Mohamed
Aidid at a militia base a few kilometers away from Yontoy
village.
</P>
<P>
These Habar Gidir men include the commander and two of his
assistants of one of those small militia bases.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, the fighting has seemed to be changing its
direction and sense.
</P>
<P>
The hostility between the two Darod sub-clans of Majerten and
Marehan is now taking a new shape escalating to include Hawiye
and Darod tribes unless something is done as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
