<HEADLINE> Fujian Accelerates Coastal Shelterbelt Planting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 26 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province,
which has already formed a basic coastal shelterbelt, is expected to
increase its coastal tree coverage rate to over 50 percent by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
It has so far planted shelter forests with a total area of
480,000 ha since 1998, when the project started, according to a
provincial official.
</P>
<P>
At present, 30 counties and cities in the province's coastal
areas have planted shelterbelts that meet state standards,
with their forest coverage rate increasing from 34.7 percent in
1988 to 43 percent, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the provincial forestry department said that the
area of the province covered by trees is expected to reach 7.06
million ha by 2000, bringing the provincial coverage rate to 60
percent by then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
