<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Organization Advises Government on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' largest organization of
employers said on Sunday the harmonization process with the
European Union (EU) must be carried out with care to avoid
negative effects on the island's economy.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of
Cyprus said that this was the basic conclusion of a study it has
conducted on the consequences of the harmonization process.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, which will be submitted to the Cypriot
government, Cyprus should seek financial aid from the EU to
support its productive sectors, which will be open to competition
from their European counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, along with five East European countries, began
accession talks with the EU last month and the harmonization
process with the organization is underway.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the liberalization of Cyprus' financial system,
the Cypriot chamber pointed out that it should not affect the
business activities on the island.
</P>
<P>
As for the free movement of labour stipulated in EU's laws, it
said employment and the social structure of Cyprus' labour force
must be taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
It expressed fear that Cyprus would have to pay a social cost
if flooded with European job seekers.
</P>
<P>
The chamber called on the government to protect the island's
lucrative offshore sector through seeking a special status in the
entry talks with the EU in a bid to preserve the booming offshore
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
