<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Warring Afghan Factions Sit Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- As a result of hectic
diplomatic efforts by the international community, the two warring
Afghan factions, the Taliban militia and the rival Northern
Alliance, sat around the negotiating table at last.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited talks between the two Afghan warring factions
opened here Sunday morning with both sides expressing optimism
about peace in their war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
It is the first face-to-face meeting between the two sides
since January last year. The meeting of the Joint Steering
Committee, which is made up of five delegates from the Taliban and
nine from the Northern Alliance, is jointly sponsored by the U.N.
and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Soon after the ceremonial session which is open to the media,
the two Afghan factions entered into their first formal session
working on the provisional agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the Northern Alliance have agreed to end their
current peace talks in Islamabad in three to five days. "The two
sides decided to work very hard to finish their work within three
consecutive days if possible but not later than five days," said
James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
During their first round of talks, the two sides reached a
five-point agreement on how they will proceed to resolve their
differences for seeking an ultimate objective of establishing
peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The agreed points include: the U.N. and OIC will be co-chairmen
of the meeting to preside over and conduct the working sessions;
Pashto and Dari (Persian) will be two official languages for the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
It also includes that decisions of the meeting will be taken
with consensus, not by voting, and if there is lack of consensus
on any matter under discussion, it would be referred to their
respective leadership, or to be postponed till the next meeting of
the Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, in the ceremonial session chaired by Pakistani Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan, head of the Taliban delegation Abdul
Wakeel said that only the proposed Ulema (religious scholars)
Commission would be able to resolve all the Afghan issues.
</P>
<P>
Wakeel said the Taliban hoped negotiations with the Northern
Alliance will yield "positive results." However, he added that if
the Ulema Commission is not recognized, "any negotiations will be
symbolic."
</P>
<P>
A written statement by the supreme Taliban leader, Mohammad
Umar, also said the Islamic militia "have suggested the Islamic
decision by Ulema, we reaffirm the same and do not want any other
formula, because we consider the decision of Ulema as sufficient
for solving all the problems."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the Taliban and the Northern Alliance still
have major differences on the formula or the agenda of the Joint
Steering Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremonial meeting, head of the Northern
Alliance delegation Fazal Hadi Shinwari said they appreciated the
efforts by the international community for bringing together "the
two brothers" to a face-to-face meeting.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the neighboring countries,
especially Pakistan, will continue to support Afghanistan's peace
process for an eventual solution of the Afghan problem.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking the neighboring countries, the U.N., as well as
OIC to make their best efforts so we could reach a conclusion
after 20 years of war," said Shinwari.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Ayub Khan, acting head of the U.N.
Special Mission on Afghanistan Ngobi and OIC Assistant Secretary
General Ibrahim Saleh Bakar also spoke at the ceremonial meeting.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the resumption of the intra-Afghan talks, saying
that it is a positive development towards the desired restoration
of peace in Afghanistan and hoping the meeting will yield positive
results.
</P>
<P>
The ceremonial meeting was also attended by diplomatic
representatives from the six neighboring countries of Afghanistan
as well as from Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The second working session between the Taliban and the Northern
Alliance is still in process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Russian Proposal, Demands Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said on Sunday that a
Russian proposal at the United Nations to end inspections of
suspected Iraqi nuclear sites fell far short of what Iraq deserved.
</P>
<P>
Humam Abdul Khaliq, minister of information and culture, was
quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency as saying that the
Russian-suggested change from inspections to a monitoring phase
"does not represent Iraq's minimal due."
</P>
<P>
The Russian proposal "addresses a partial situation," and "if
this is all the U.N. Security Council's April discussions would
lead to," it does not meet Iraq's expectations, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Russia floated a draft resolution calling for an end
to inspections of Iraq's suspected nuclear sites because there was
no proof that Iraq is still working on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Khaliq said this resolution "would serve the American tactics
intended to derail the course of discussions from their core and
gain time to prolong the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that all proscribed weapons under U.N. resolution
687, and their related facilities and equipment, have been
dismantled since late 1991.
</P>
<P>
The inspections of Iraq's presidential compounds, brokered by
U.N. chief Kofi Annan in February to end a crisis over weapons
inspections between Iraq and the U.N., have come up with nothing
of prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Hence, he said, the U.N. sanctions, already seven years old,
were expected to have been lifted long time ago.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Iraq still hoped the Security Council's
bi-annual review of the sanctions regime, scheduled to start on
Monday, might lead to the removal of sanctions. "Iraq is waiting
for this result in sincere recognition of its dear sacrifices," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, the chief U.N. arms inspector, however, said in
a recent report to the United Nations that his Special Commission
on disarming Iraq had made "virtually no progress" over the past
six months in determining if Iraq is clean of banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
"If the world and fair-minded people would like to see the
relationship between Iraq and the Security Council and its Special
Commission resting on a basis of fairness," Khaliq said, the
subject of sanctions should be tackled in all sincerity toward
their immediate lifting.
</P>
<P>
"A mere approval of the Russian proposal shall not bend Iraq's
will of determination to do what is right," he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the statements made by Iraq's Revolution
Command Council and cabinet should be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
The statements demand immediate implementation of paragraph 22
of the U.N. resolution 687, which provides for easing of sanctions
once Iraq's nuclear, chemical, biological weapons and ballistic
missiles have been scrapped and steps taken to ensure they can not
be rebuilt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
