<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Holds First Smoke Combating Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Minister of Health
Adel Al-Subeih Sunday warned dangerous consequences of smoking
especially among the youngsters in the Gulf state while
inaugurating a regional anti-smoking conference here.
</P>
<P>
The conference, first of its kind in Kuwait, was organized by
Kuwaiti Society for the Prevention of Smoking and Cancer in
cooperation with the Kuwait Foundation for the Advancement of
Sciences and the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day conference, smoking combating experts from
Saudi Arabia, Oman and Kuwait will present papers on means and
experiences in fighting the health harming habit.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is one of the largest cigarette consuming country in
the Middle East region and smoking habit is quickly finding its
way among the school students.
</P>
<P>
Al-Subeih said in his inaugural speech that 50 percent of
deaths in Kuwait Pectoral Hospital occurred as a result of lung
cancer diseases, of which smoking is a main factor.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the majority of heart patients under
40 years of age in Kuwait are smokers. Patients who are smokers
cost his ministry triple treatment than the non-smokers in the
country, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also reviewed Kuwaiti government's efforts in combating
smoking through the forbidding of smoking advertising in the
official media sources and public places, limiting the maximum
nicotine and tar percentage, increasing the customs tax on
cigarettes and printing the health-warning on the cigarette
packs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
