<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law to Help Deter Youth Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
deliberated a draft law on the prevention of juvenile delinquency,
the first of its kind in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
Hou Zongbin, chairman of the Committee for Internal and
Judicial Affairs of the National People's Congress (NPC), said
that the aim of the law is to create a social environment which is
conducive to the healthy growth of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The draft law underlines the guardianship and educational
responsibilities of families and schools. It also makes clear the
responsibilities of relevant government departments as regards
cultural affairs which affect young people.
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulates that aid should be offered to
disadvantaged children, such as those with divorced parents or
problems attending school.
</P>
<P>
Guo Xiang, a professor at the China University of Political
Science and Law, said that most youngsters aged 17 to 22 who break
the law have little knowledge of the law. "Therefore, priority
should be given to prevention," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first peak period of teenage crimes in New China came about
during the "cultural revolution" (1966-1976), Guo noted, and "the
second peak came in the late 1980s."
</P>
<P>
He warned that in the near future crimes specifically related
to only-children will be emerge as a new problem.
</P>
<P>
The draft law deliberated today at the second meeting of the
NPC's Standing Committee applies to youngsters between the ages of
14 and 18.
</P>
<P>
The average age of criminals has been decreasing since the 1970s,
and teenage crimes have become a factor affecting social stability.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of teenage criminals to other youngsters in the same
age group doubled during the 1986-1995 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
