<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Discuss Yellow River Anti-Flood Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A group of officials and
experts from Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Shandong provinces
gathered here April 24-26 to discuss anti-flood work on the Yellow
River.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held by the Yellow River Anti-Flood
Headquarters, which is based in this capital of Henan.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, the second-largest in China, was prone to
endemic flooding and the accompanying property and human losses
before the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
In the past 48 years the river has not caused any major
disasters or losses, thanks to the efforts of local people and
governments at all levels.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the meeting urged people to be on their
guard for possible severe floods this year, because ``the
anti-flooding facilities along the river are aging and eroded''.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that projects to repair or rebuild the dikes and
dams, especially in dangerous sections, must be completed on time
before the flood season comes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts must be made to accomplish forecasts of
water levels at seven leading hydrometric stations on the lower
reaches of the river, and for the working out of plans for
evacuation in case of floods, as well as other related matters,
according to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The participants also discussed flood-prevention measures
for the Xiaolangdi Hydropower Project that is being built near
Luoyang City, Henan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
