<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st SAARC Information Ministers' Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The first SAARC (South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation) Information Ministers'
Meeting ended here Sunday after adopting a "Dhaka Communique"
which calls for greater cooperation among members countries.
</P>
<P>
Greater cooperation among SAARC member countries plays a vital
role in promoting peace, progress and harmony in South Asia, the
communique, a "plan of action on media and information," said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it encourages greater flow of information in the
region on all issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The statement sets goals and objectives for regional
cooperation in media and information, such as "to generate,
disseminate and exchange information materials" in various areas,
"to promote the optimal utilization of available resources and
facilities" and "upgrade the professionalism of media persons,"
and "to enable member countries to fully benefit from the use of
new technologies."
</P>
<P>
It calls for free flow of information and all kinds of
publications, more cooperation among news agencies of SAARC
countries, and easier travel for media persons within the region.
</P>
<P>
SAARC members will examine the financial and technical
feasibility of establishing a SAARC satellite, and explore the
feasibility of setting up a SAARC information center and a media
development fund, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, which started Saturday, was initiated
by Bangladesh at a SAARC Council of Ministers' meeting in the
Maldives last year.
</P>
<P>
Five information ministers from Bangladesh, Pakistan, India,
Sri Lanka and India attended the meeting, while the Maldives was
represented by a three-member delegation and Bhutan by its charge
d'affairs in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, established in December 1985, groups Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Northern Airlines to Open New Air Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 26 (Xinhua) -- China Northern Airlines, based
in this capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province, will open
four new air routes to Japan beginning May 19.
</P>
<P>
This will bring China Northern's total number of international
air routes to 14, according to an executive of the company.
</P>
<P>
The four new air routes will be Shenyang-Osaka-Shenyang,
Harbin-Niigata-Harbin, Dalian-Toyoma-Dalian and
Shenyang-Sapporo-Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
There will be two flights per week, on Tuesdays and Fridays, on
the Shenyang-Osaka-Shenyang route, which will go into service May
19.
</P>
<P>
The Harbin-Niigata-Harbin route will begin June 1, with only
one flight a week, on Mondays. Dalian-Toyoma-Dalian route will
start June 17, with flights Wednesdays and Saturdays. The
Shenyang-Sapporo-Shenyang route will go into service June 28, with
only one flight a week, every Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The four new routes will be opened in accordance with relevant
agreements signed by the Chinese and Japanese civil aviation
administrations in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
More new air routes are expected to be opened by other airline
companies of the two countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
China Northern Airlines now operates more than 150 domestic and
overseas air routes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
