<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports Remain Brisk in Major Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The demand for Chinese
commodities remains strong in China's major overseas markets,
despite the negative impact on the country's exports caused by the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
This was proved by the fact that China's exports to regions
outside Asia increased by over 17 percent in the first three
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
This can also be seen here at the ongoing 83rd China Import and
Export Commodities Fair.
</P>
<P>
Business people from China's conventional export markets, such
as the countries of the European Union and North America, as well
as Japan, and Hong Kong and Macao, have been active in purchasing
at the fair, making up around 70 percent of the business people
attending the fair.
</P>
<P>
Craig Fleming, a sales manager from Roman Bank House of
Britain, said that he would buy more Chinese-made paper flowers at
the fair, at least no less than the company bought last year.
</P>
<P>
So far at the 16-day fair, launched April 15, China has signed
deals for exports of machinery and electrical products topping 1.5
billion US dollars-worth.
</P>
<P>
Business people from the United States, the European Union,
Japan, Hong Kong and Macao have ordered Chinese commodities worth
nearly 600 million US dollars, up 12 percentage points over the
figure for the previous fair.
</P>
<P>
However, China's business volume with Southeast Asian countries
declined by some 70 percent at the fair.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has signed export contracts at the fair for
light industrial and arts and crafts products exceeding one
billion US dollars-worth, mainly with the United States, Hong
Kong, the EU countries and Japan, representing an increase of more
than 14 percent over the same period of the previous fair.
</P>
</TEXT>
