<HEADLINE> Asian Development Needs More Technical Aid: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Asia's developing countries need
more technical assistance to manage and initiate structural reform
programs and strategies which can meet challenges of a different
nature and magnitude, the Asian Development Bank (finance) said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Asian nations have traditionally called for foreign assistance
to finance physical projects such as irrigation systems and roads,
but changes in their economic environments have led them to also
seek more technical assistance, which is designed to help physical
projects work," said the Manila-based bank in its annual report
for 1997, which was released here.
</P>
<P>
As a major provider of technical assistance in the Asian and
Pacific region, the bank provided 162.5 million U.S. dollars in
technical aid to finance 298 projects in its member economies in
1997, compared to 41.9 million dollars for 135 projects the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The ADB, which provides both financing of projects and
technical assistance, said the role of technical assistance has
been increasing and will continue to grow, given changes in
development environments.
</P>
<P>
The bank said its technical aid is aimed at assisting its
developing members in identifying, formulating and implementing
projects; improving their institutional capabilities and
formulating development strategies; promoting technology transfer,
and fostering regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the bank's technical assistance included a project in
China to promote energy-saving construction materials, and a
project in India to promote public finance reforms, and the
establishment of a tender support bureau in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The bank said many developing countries in Asia need to enhance
their capacity to manage and initiate development and economic
policies as they switch to market-oriented, outward-looking
economic management strategies and undertake policy and regulatory
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Many of the region's centrally planned economies are also in
transition towards a market economy, and technical assistance is
needed to help them create and develop a set of institutions for a
market economy, it said.
</P>
<P>
"To assist developing member economies effectively in this
changing environment, the bank cannot help but make its services
further broad-based," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Technical assistance has become a key strategic tool for
development assistance," it said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB's technical assistance operations are financed through
grants or loans, or a combination of both. Grants are funded by
the bank's Technical Assistance Special Fund based on voluntary
contribution from its members, and the Japan Special Fund, a
united contribution from the Japanese government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
