<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Optimistic About Prospects of Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite the current financial
crisis in Asia, the longer-term outlook for the Asian economy "is
far from bleak," the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Human capacities have not been destroyed, social and physical
infrastructure remain largely intact, and there has been a
strengthening of policies and institutional structures that
promote openness and macro-economic stability," the bank said in
its annual report for 1997 which was released here.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the capacity for resources mobilization,
reasonably good infrastructure, favorable demographics, an open
trading system and a general commitment to macro-economic prudence
-- all these factors should stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
"In time, structural weakness in financial systems can and will
be rectified, more efficient capital markets will evolve and
foreign capital will return," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic growth will resume once appropriate adjustment
policies are implemented and take effect," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank admitted that fast growth in Asia is unlikely
to resume quickly as the necessary institutional response to the
crisis cannot be implemented overnight.
</P>
<P>
For some economies, it said, the road back may be "longer than
for others," but provided policy corrections are made and
institutional reforms carried through, the foundations which
propelled fast growth in the past should once again come to the
fore.
</P>
<P>
On the consequences of the crisis, the bank said that Asia's
economic progress was set back significantly by precipitous falls
in the values of currencies and stock markets that began in
mid-1997, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the repercussions of these disturbances are still
being felt through the region and beyond.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook--1998" published last week,
the bank said the Asian crisis contributed to a further slowdown
in the growth rate to 6.1 percent in 1997 from 7.5 percent in 1996
and the growth pace is projected at about 4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The bank said South Korea and most of Southeast Asia are now
undergoing wrenching macro-economic and sectoral adjustments, but
the implications for real economic activity, as opposed to the
financial sector, are only gradually being revealed.
</P>
<P>
"The social consequences of the crisis are likely to be
serious," the bank warned.
</P>
<P>
It said many of those least able to protect themselves, such as
migrant workers, will be among those most severely affected.
</P>
<P>
The expectations of many of Asia's emerging middle classes have
also suffered, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Social safety nets, which are weak or poorly developed in many
places, are coming under increasing stress," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank promised that it will continue to assist its
developing members to address such difficulties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
