<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Responds Quickly to Asian Crisis, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank said
Monday that it has monitored the Asian financial crisis closely
since it started in mid-1997 and determined appropriate response.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report for 1997, which was released here, the
bank said it liaised closely with its members, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank, and bilateral donors to
develop its interventions in the 10-month old crisis.
</P>
<P>
"These efforts culminated in program loans to the Republic of
Korea (South Korea) and Thailand, and a pledge of assistance to
Indonesia," it said.
</P>
<P>
The loan to South Korea was the bank's first to the country
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
"These loans illustrated the bank's ability to respond rapidly
to the needs of the region," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the financial sector loans to South Korea and Thailand
from the bank's ordinary capital resources boosted total ADB
lending for the year to 9.4 billion U.S. dollars, nearly 4 billion
dollars more than its lending in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the financial sector received nearly 50 percent
of total lending," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
As the crisis deepened and broadened, the bank said, it
approved a 300 million dollar financial markets reform program
loan for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The program was designed to strengthen market regulation and
supervision, improve risk management, facilitate investor access
to domestic financial markets and develop long-term institutional
sources of funds by promoting an integrated system of pension and
provident funds.
</P>
<P>
For South Korea, the bank said, it approved a 4
billion-U.S.-dollar program loan for financial sector reforms in
three major areas -- capacity building of banking and non-bank
financial institutions; building financial market infrastructure;
and improving corporate accounting and disclosure standards.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, according to the bank, it has been working on a
1.5 billion-U.S.-dollar capital market reform program to improve
the country's regulatory and supervisory functions, develop the
fixed income securities and financial derivatives markets and
strengthen the institutional capability of contractual savings
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the bank is expected to become involved with
restructuring the banking system, focusing on private national
banks and regional development banks," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank is a multilateral development finance
institution, whose capital stock is owned by 56 members from the
Asia-Pacific region and outside the region. The bank is engaged in
promoting the economic and social progress of its developing
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
