<HEADLINE> Yemeni Parliament Speaker Optimistic on Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Parliament Speaker
Sheikh Abdullah Bin Hussein Al-Ahmar has expressed optimism on
prospects of improving ties with Kuwait which became strained
since the 1991 Gulf War, the official Kuwait News Agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"There is sincere desire for cooperation for the benefit of
the two countries," Al-Ahmar said in Yemeni capital Sanaa in an
interview with the news agency.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to a future marked with restoration of Arab
solidarity and this requires concessions from all of us," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti-Yemeni relations turned sour after the Gulf War
because Sanaa sided with Iraq during Iraqi seven month-occupation
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait downgraded its diplomatic representation in Yemen to the
level of Charge D'Affaires in 1991 while Yemen closed its embassy
in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Prospects of improving bilateral ties have become brighter
since early last year when Kuwait officially declared the
intention to start a reconciliatory process with the Arab
countries that supported Iraq during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
A Kuwaiti educational delegation visited Sanaa last July on
the first such mission after the ties were strained. Last month
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh in what was seen as a good
will towards Kuwait said the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait caused
dissension among the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Al-Ahmar also said that his country backs
any effort that would lead to resolving the issue of Prisoners of
War (POWs) between Iraq and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been sensitive to the improvement of
relations between Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait said that Baghdad still detains 625 Kuwaiti POWs in
Iraqi jails and has frequently urged Iraq to release them. But
Baghdad said those POWs were missing during turmoils in southern
Iraq following the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
