<HEADLINE> S. African Delegation to Tour Maghreb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 26 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Affairs Deputy Minister Aziz Pahad Sunday left for Algeria, the
first stop on a visit to the Maghreb countries to promote
economic ties with the region.
</P>
<P>
He will be accompanied by a delegation of senior government
officials and South African business representatives, the Foreign
Affairs Department said.
</P>
<P>
The visit is to introduce the South African business community
to opportunities in the Maghreb, the northern African region
which consists of Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Libya and
Mauritania, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The region, strategically situated in the Mediterranean basin,
has a population of 70 million.
</P>
<P>
In Algeria, Pahad and his Algerian counterpart, Lachene
Moussaoui, will co-chair the first meeting of the joint bilateral
commission, aimed at establishing a legal framework to facilitate
business and other exchanges between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Pahad will sign agreements on merchant shipping and air
services, science and technology, agriculture, tourism, customs
and sport and on the avoidance of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Pahad will proceed to Tunisia and Libya where he will hold
talks with officials of both governments.
</P>
<P>
Following this visit, ministerial delegations from both
Morocco and Tunisia are expected in South Africa in mid-May, the
Foreign Affairs department said. 
</P>
