<HEADLINE> Blast Rocks N.Ireland After Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) - An explosion damaged a Catholic bar
and restaurant near Armagh city in Northern Ireland overnight but
there were no casualties, BBC TV reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The area around the bar was sealed off and families forced to
leave a number of nearby homes. The BBC quoted a police spokesman
as saying the cause of the blast was unknown.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that it was not a major explosion
and an Army bomb disposal team was sent to the scene.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident Saturday, police arrested two men in
connection with the murder of a roman Catholic student.
</P>
<P>
The student, Ciaran Heffron, was the latest victim of sectarian
violence that persists in Northern Ireland despite a peace accord
was signed this month.
</P>
<P>
Heffron was killed only a day after two key Protestant
guerrilla groups announced their support for the April 10 peace
deal reached by eight main Protestant and Catholic political
parties and the British and Irish governments. 
</P>
