<HEADLINE> India Objects to Pakistan's Reference to Kashmir at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- India strongly objected to Pakistan
raising the Kashmir issue at the first SAARC Information
Ministers' meeting which started here Saturday, press reports said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Indian Information Sushma Swaraj voiced the objection when her
Pakistani counterpart, Mushahid Hossain, brought in the Kashmir
issue Saturday in his presentation during the closed-door working
session of the two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
Terming the reference to Kashmir as "uncalled for," Swaraj said
it was against relevant articles of the SAARC Charter, which she
said prohibited the raising of bilateral and contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
The Indian minister asked the chairman of the working session,
Bangladeshi State Minister for Information Abud Sayeed, to expunge
the reference to Kashmir from the proceedings of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Sayeed said any reference to contentious issues,
which negated the SAARC Charter, would automatically be deleted
from the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Information ministers from Bangladesh, Pakistan, India, Sri
Lanka and Nepal are participating in the meeting, which was
initiated by Bangladesh last year. The Maldives is represented by
a three-member delegation and Bhutan by its Charge d'Affaires in
Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC),
established in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
