<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Factions Agree to End Talks in 3-5 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
and the rival Northern Alliance have agreed to end their current
peace talks in Islamabad in three to five days, a senior U.N.
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides decided to work very hard to finish their work
within three consecutive days if possible but not later than five
days," said James Ngobi, Head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said the Joint Steering Committee, which is made up of
five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, spent their first
session discussing the procedures and reached agreement on a
number of procedures.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were now engaged in working on the provisional
agenda, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official, who is presiding over the intra-Afghan
talks, said the Taliban and the alliance agreed that the United
Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
should be designated as the co-chairmen of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the statement on the proceedings of each
session will be made only by the co-chairmen on behalf of the
committee after the text of the statement has been approved by the
committee as a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
No other statement will be taken as the official one
representing the committee if it is not made by the co-chairmen,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the two sides agreed they will reach agreement by
consensus and not by voting, he said.
</P>
<P>
If there is lack of consensus on any matter under discussion,
that matter would either be referred to the respective leaderships
or would be postponed until a future meeting of the committee.
</P>
<P>
The on-going meeting between Taliban and the alliance, which
started here Sunday morning, is jointly sponsored by the U.N. and
the OIC. It is the first face-to-face encounter between the two
Afghan rivals in more than a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
