<HEADLINE> Iran: U.S. Should Look "More Humane" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has said that it will be "wiser" for the United States to
change its outlooks and pursue "more humane approach" towards the
world, the official IRNA news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lambasting U.S. economic sanctions against Tehran, he told
visiting Japanese State Secretary for Foreign Affairs Masahiko
Komura Saturday that the U.S. can no longer dictate its volition
over the others.
</P>
<P>
Citing Iran as a successful case of breaking up U.S. isolation,
Khatami said his country is doing well through self-sufficiency
and has satisfactorily mended fences with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has imposed various sanctions on Iran ever since the
beginning of the Islamic Revolution of Iran in 1979. Washington
broke off relations with Tehran after radical Iranian students
occupied the U.S. embassy and took the staffers hostage in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a warning apparently to the U.S., the president said
exertion of pressure and intimidation will only lead to violence
in the world.
</P>
<P>
World peace rests only with elimination of domineering policies
and promotion of respect for the rights of others and honor for
mankind, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. should transform its outlooks to the world including
Iran so that it can enter the 21st century with new perceptions in
the active international arena, Khatami added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Iran-Japan ties, Khatami told Komura that it
was an appropriate time for the expansion of bilateral cooperation
in all the possible economic, technical and technological spheres.
</P>
<P>
Komura said that Japan looks at Iran as a friend while
maintaining a cordial relation with the U.S.. He also expressed
hope that obstacles against re-establishing Tehran-Washington
relations will be removed.
</P>
<P>
Komura also handed over a message from Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto to Khatami. He left here Sunday morning after
wrapping up a four-day official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
