<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Support for Syria, Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iranian First Vice President
Hassan Habibi has reiterated Iran's support for the stance of
Syria and Lebanon demanding unconditional Israeli withdrawal from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with visiting Syrian First Vice President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam on Saturday night, Habibi said that if the
idea of the Israeli offer is to implement the U.N. resolution 425,
there should be no strings attached, the Iranian official news
agency IRNA reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Cabinet formally approved the resolution on April 1
and offered to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon provided
negotiated security arrangement are agreed by the Lebanese
government.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon established with the aim to protect its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria, which closely coordinate their
Mideast policies, firmly rejected the offer on the grounds that it
contradicted the resolution which calls for an unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The two countries want the Israeli withdrawal unconditional and
simultaneous with an Israeli pullback from the Golan Heights, which
Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Habibi stressed that Israel should not only pull out of south
Lebanon but also from all the occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam, who arrived here Saturday afternoon on a three-day
visit, said that the Israeli "plot" aims to detach the Lebanese
from the Syrians and to destroy the resistance movement of the
Lebanese nation.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed satisfaction over growing trend of bilateral
relations, saying that close cooperation between Syria and Iran
will lead to restoration of peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reviewed regional and international
developments, the role of Iran and Syria in defusing regional
crisis, and problems facing the world of Islam, according to IRNA.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views about respect to Iraq's territorial
integrity, non-interference of foreign powers in domestic affairs
of the regional countries, the Palestinian resistance movement,
cooperation among Islamic countries and defusing the Middle East
crisis through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
They voiced concern over Turkey-Israel military cooperation,
believing that it is to the detriment of regional security and
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
