<HEADLINE> Israeli Youth Disappointed With Government: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of the 50th
anniversary celebration in Israel, most Israeli youth said they
were disappointed with the government, the English daily The
Jerusalem Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a poll, conducted early this year among 423
Jewish youngsters aged 13-18, as saying that only 26 percent of
them were proud of the government, while 68 percent were
disappointed and 6 percent indifferent.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which had a margin of error of 4.8 percent, also
showed that 66 percent of the youth were disappointed with the
Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
On the other side, only 31 percent were disappointed with
the Jewish state, while a total of 65 percent said they were
proud of the country.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the poll showed that the youngsters are proudest
of the Israeli Defense Forces, with 87 percent saying they
were proud of the army, 11 percent disappointed and 2 percent
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
Shmuel Abuav, head of Israeli Union of Local Authorities,
said the poll showed that the army is seen as an apolitical
body that has values and goals with which the youngsters
identify.
</P>
<P>
But the youngsters tend to dissociate themselves from the
government and Knesset, which are by their nature political
bodies, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
