<HEADLINE> Palestinian State to Be Set up in 1999: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- An independent Palestinian state
will be set up in May 1999, Secretary General of the Palestine
Liberation Organization Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians will declare the establishment of the
Palestinian independent state in May next year on the basis of
Oslo agreement signed with Israel and in accordance with the
United Nations Security Council resolutions 242 and 338," he told
the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of the Israeli people do not oppose the setting
up of the Palestinian state, said the Palestinian official.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
last year when Israel began construction of the Jewish housing
project on Har Homa in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians
wants as the capital of their would-be state.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated over the lack of progress in the peace process,
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Palestinian officials have recently repeatedly announced their
determination to declare an independent Palestinian state in 1999,
regardless of concluding a peace treaty with Israel or not.
</P>
<P>
Abbas, who is better known as Abu Mazen, called upon the
U.S. to double its efforts to salvage the stalled Mideast peace
drive.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross arrived in Jerusalem
Saturday, together with U.S. Assistant Secretary of State and
former U.S. ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk, to begin a new
round of mediation aimed at reviving the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross will demand that Israel accept the U.S. proposal for troop
withdrawal from a further 13.1 percent from the West Bank over 12
weeks, with each step met by Palestinian security measures.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Abbas expressed hope that Ross would succeed
in persuading the Israelis to accept the U.S. ideas, thus paving
the way for the planned four-way talks in London to be co-hosted
on May 4 by British Prime Minister Tony Blair and U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
