<HEADLINE> Landmines Disable About 160,000 Cambodians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Out of a thousand Cambodians
nearly 13 have been disabled by landmines, the highest rate in the
world, said a recent government report.
</P>
<P>
As a result of three decades of wars, Cambodia now has 158,000
people who have been disabled by landmines. The country has a
population of 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations landmine-clearing agency estimated that more
than six million landmines are strewn across the country, mostly
in Thai-Cambodian border areas.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that each month some 150 to 200 people -- 40
percent of them women and children -- lose their limbs or lives to
these explosives.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government has tried to train these crippled and
create jobs for them, but fund shortage has greatly hindered such
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
