<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Talks a Breakthrough: OIC Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the
Steering Committee is an "important breakthrough in the continuous
efforts to restore peace in Afghanistan," a senior official of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time the opposing sides are meeting
face-to-face, with open minds to discuss their differences with a
view to reaching an amicable solution," said OIC Assistant
Secretary General Ibrahim Saleh Bakar at the inaugural session of
the meeting in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Bakar said OIC Secretary General Azeddine Laraki welcomes "this
encouraging development" towards a peaceful solution to the
protracted Afghan conflict and hopes that both sides will make
concessions and compromises so that a lasting peace can be
achieved in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bakar also said any meeting like the one between the Taliban
and the rival Northern Alliance "cannot be expected to be smooth
and easy."
</P>
<P>
He advised the participants to remember that they were all
Afghans, having the same religious and cultural background.
</P>
<P>
"They should also remember that their decisions in the coming
days will be reflective on the Afghan nation as a whole especially
the helpless women and children who are always the most affected
victims of any civil war," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the amount of destruction and loss of lives that the
civil war is causing is too great to be left to continue
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
It is this reason that the OIC and the international community
attach great importance to the Steering Committee meeting as a
first step to resolve the Afghan conflict, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee meeting had been made possible due to
untiring efforts of well-meaning individuals, countries and
organizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the participants were holding their
deliberations in an atmosphere of peace, brotherhood and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
"May we succeed in our endeavor to bring back normalcy to
Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural session earlier, Pakistani foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan reiterated his country's stand that the
Afghan problem should be solved through peaceful negotiations
under the auspices of the U.N. and the OIC."
</P>
<P>
"It is gratifying to see that this process is taking a
meaningful start today," he said. "It is a great development and
we should all put our sincere efforts to help this process reach a
meaningful conclusion."
</P>
<P>
He urged all the participants to commence with a spirit of
accommodation for the general good of all Afghans irrespective of
their sect of ethnicity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
