<HEADLINE> Olympic Official Hopes Ice Dancing Dropped from Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior International Olympic
Committee official is suggesting that ice dancing be dropped from
the winter games because of the wide accusation of result-fixing.
</P>
<P>
Dick Pound, an IOC vice president from Canada, said in Sydney
on Sunday the image of the Olympics has been marred by what he
described as blatant, predetermined standings in the dance
competition.
</P>
<P>
Pound was reacting to the judging controversy at the Nagano
Games in February when the Canadian pair of Shae-Lynn Bourne and
Victor Kraatz were deprived of what many thought should have been
at least a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Pound said he would raise the issue at the IOC executive board
meetings in Sydney this week and would suggest ice dancing be
dropped until the judging system is deemed fair and
comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
Many thought Bourne-Kraatz skated even better than the gold
medalists, and their coach, Natalia Dubova, claimed the judges
conspired to keep the Canadians off the medals podium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
