<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Team Set Up to Help Improve Kenya's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- An inter-parties forum on the
economic crisis facing Kenya has unanimously agreed to set up a
19-member parliamentary committee to facilitate parliamentary
contribution to improve economic governance in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Nation said Sunday that the committee chaired by
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae was mandated to seek ways to
salvage the East African country's economy.
</P>
<P>
After two-day consultations at the forum which ended Saturday,
participants recommended that Kenyan Parliament should use all
mechanisms available to fight corruption in the country and to
control government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The forum, which was attended by 162 members of Parliament
from both the ruling and opposition parties, officials from the
World Bank and heads of diplomatic missions, asked Kenyan finance
minister to prepare short- and long-term economic recovery
programs, and present them to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the forum sponsored by the World Bank, the
U.S. government and the German NGO of the Friedrich Ebert Siftung
recommended that the number of government ministries should be
cut down from 25 to 18.
</P>
<P>
It was also resolved that donors at the forum agreed any
initiative toward economic recovery should be a kenya-led
strategy, unlike in the past when the Bretton Woods institutions
have imposed prescriptions on Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session held in the port city of Mombasa last
Friday, Kenyan Finance Minister Nyachae said that the government
has no money under the present situation of a "tattered economy"
and corruption in high places had contributed directly to the
mismanagement of Kenya's financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the minister noted that Kenyans were
noticeably poorer today than they were 18 years ago with the
income every Kenyan had falling from 21,000 Kenyan Shillings in
1980 to 15,000 Shillings in 1998, or from 420 U.S. Dollars to
260 Dollars, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The estimated proportion of the population living below the
poverty line has risen steadily from 44 percent in 1989 to around
50 percent today, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
