<HEADLINE> Beijing to Relocate Households Residing in Imperial Garden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will spend more than 100
million yuan (12 million US dollars) to relocate all 615
households within the ruins of Yuanmingyuan, an imperial garden in
northwestern part of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The work is expected to be completed before October 1, 1999,
the 50th founding anniversary of new China. Those households will
be moved to new buildings outside the park.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Haidian District government, where
Yuanmingyuan is located, said the move is necessary to preserve
the imperial park.
</P>
<P>
Yuanmingyuan covers an area of 350 hectares. It was completed
in 1859 after 150 years of construction. In that era, emperors
spent most of their time in the garden.
</P>
<P>
However, Yuanmingyuan was burned and destroyed by British and
French allied forces in 1860.
</P>
<P>
The present park was built on the ruins of Yuanmingyuan and
opened to the public in 1986. The park now occupies 167 hectares.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
