<HEADLINE> Only Ulema Commission to Resolve Afghan Issue:Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Taliban's
five-member delegation to the talks with the rival Northern
Alliance said Sunday that only the proposed Ulema (religious
scholars) Commission would be able to resolve all the Afghan
issues.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremonial meeting of the Joint Steering
Committee which began in Islamabad earlier in the day, Abdul
Wakeel said the Taliban hoped the negotiations with the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance will yield "positive results."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, if the Ulema Commission is not recognized,
"any negotiations will be symbolic."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban representative said the Taliban are entering into
the negotiations with "sincerity," and are ready to work for a
peaceful settlement of the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Northern Alliance to reciprocate the Taliban's
"sincerity" for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are not working for personal profits. We have an important
historical task on our shoulders. Let's work for peace and
stability in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is made possible by efforts of the U.N., the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), and Afghanistan's
six neighboring countries as well as Russia and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
A written statement by Taliban leader Mohammad Umar also said
the Islamic militia "have suggested the Islamic decision by Ulema,
we reaffirm the same and do not have any other formula, because we
consider the decision of Ulema as sufficient for solving all the
problems."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, the head of the Northern Alliance
delegation, Fazal Hadi Shinwari, said they welcomed Wakeel's
speech and appreciated the efforts for bringing together "the two
brothers" to a face-to-face meeting.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the neighboring countries,
especially Pakistan, will continue to support Afghanistan's peace
process for an eventual solution to the Afghan problem.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking the neighboring countries, the U.N., as well as
OIC to make their best efforts so we could reach a conclusion
after 20 years of war," Shinwari said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two warring Afghan factions, sponsored
jointly by the U.N. and OIC, is the first face-to-face parley
since the Taliban took over the Afghan capital of Kabul in
September 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
