<HEADLINE> Confusion, Panic Hit Zimbabwe's Financial Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- There was confusion and near
panic in Zimbabwean financial markets last week as rumors of
serious problems at one of the merchant banks circulated, the
Sunmail reported.
</P>
<P>
Investors and financial institutions were extremely nervous
and checks started bouncing, the Sunmail said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar came under pressure due to reduced
tobacco inflows and reports of a surge in importer demand. On
Thursday, indicative rates for the local currency were 17 to the
U.S. Dollar, representing a depreciation of around five percent
from the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The local currency is set to fall further unless the reserve
bank intervenes.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the news on inflation was not good either. The
consumer price index for March rose by 3.9 percentage points to
27.9 percent on year-to-year basis. Food prices rose by 33.7
percent over the same period. When food is factored out, the
underlying rate of inflation stood at 24.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The outlook is not encouraging. Broad money supply reportedly
was rising at annual rate of 33.7 percent in January and in that
month the trade deficit widened to 8.4 million U.S. Dollars
compared to 6.1 million Dollars in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
