<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Encouraged by Afghan Factions' Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations felt
encouraged by the resumption of peace talks between Afghanistan's
Islamic Taliban militia and their rival Northern Alliance, the
head of the U.N. Special Mission on Afghanistan said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremonial meeting of the Steering Committee,
James Ngobi also expressed the hope that the joint committee would
work with "full dedication" and pave way for the establishment of
the Ulema (religious scholar) Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee is made up of five Taliban and nine
Northern Alliance delegates.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, sponsored jointly by the U.N. and the Organization
of the Islamic Conference (OIC), is the first face-to-face
encounter between the two Afghan rivals in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
"If you are faithful to your commitment to the real peace, the
U.N. will always at your help," he said.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the mediating role of Pakistan and U.N.
Special Envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi who has been visiting
the region in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the key to peace lies in the hands of the
Afghan warring factions themselves.
</P>
<P>
"We are just playing the role of "facilitator," he said. "If
you want durable peace, then put down your arms and sit for the
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
described the talks as a "meaningful start" towards the
restoration of durable peace in that war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The on-going intra-Afghan talks were made possible by the
hectic diplomatic efforts by the U.N., OIC, Pakistan, the U.S. and
other countries who have influence in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Ulema Commission, proposed by the Taliban, will bear the
responsibility for deciding the future political set-up in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Steering Committee is yet another attempt to iron out
the differences between the Taliban and the alliance after the
former rejected the latter's first Ulema list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
