<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Anticipates Publication of U.S. Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- As United States peace envoy
Dennis Ross began his new mission here, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu believed Washington is to present its plan for
a 13.1 percent pullback next week, a newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The English daily The Jerusalem Post reported that Netanyahu
told senior ministers Saturday night that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will officially present its peace plan during
her upcoming London talks on May 4.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held the previously unannounced Inner Cabinet meeting
at his residence just ahead of his meeting with Ross, who arrived
here Saturday in company with Assistant Secretary of State for
Near East Affairs and former U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin
Indyk.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Cabinet also includes Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
No details were disclosed about the three-hour Netanyahu-Ross
meeting in the Prime Minister's Office Saturday night, but top on
Ross' agenda was to persuade Netanyahu to accept the U.S. proposal
for a 13.1 percent redeployment in the West Bank so to break the
year-long deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross's visit will also lay the ground for the four-way London
talks to be co-hosted by British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
Albright, who will hold separate meetings with Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is expected to launch his last-ditch efforts to
disuade the U.S. from publishing the peace plan. Netanyahu
reportedly told his senior ministers that unless the size of a
third redeployment is set, Israel would not agree to a second
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the Israeli government has not indicated any
willingness to accept any proposal calling for more than 9
percent troop pullback in the West Bank. But some reports said
Netanyahu is considering a 11 percent pullback in exchange for
PNA's promise to increase fight against terrorism and enter the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross will meet with Arafat Sunday and return to Jerusalem to
hold another around of talks with Netanyahu. As a compromise, the
PNA has already endorsed the U.S. proposal for a 13.1 percent
redeployment and is demanding the U.S. pressure Israel to accept
the plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu is to reconvene the Inner Cabinet meeting
Sunday to discuss the Ross' mission and to coordinate the Israeli
position on the further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Noting the depth of the Israeli-Palestinian dispute over the
redeployment, the U.S. has downplayed expectation for a dramatic
breakthrough from Ross' new round of intensive mediation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
