<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Approach Mt. Apo in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Sunday ordered government departments to mobilize local disaster
coordinating councils to quickly create firebreaks against the
forest fires raging near the summit of Mt. Apo in the Southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the presidential office,
Ramos also ordered Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat, who is also
chairman of the National Disaster Coordinating Council, to utilize
all other measures to bring the fires under control.
</P>
<P>
Ramos asked Abat to submit to him a feedback by Monday on the
action, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that since Friday morning, the fires have
destroyed an undetermined number of hectares of forest within the
forest reservation of the Philippine National Oil Company near
Lake Macadac and the peak of Mt. Apo, in the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The fires, which might have been triggered by slash-and-burn
farming, are threatening the ecosystem of the country's highest
peak and a geothermal power plant there, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The 9,690-foot-high Mt. Apo, an active volcano, is home to the
endangered monkey-eating eagle and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
During the Last three months, forest fires have hit eight
provinces in the country. In Palawan Province alone, 15,000
hectares of forest were destroyed by the fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
