<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Calls for Sustained Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Representatives attending a
meeting arranged by the International Labor Organization (ILO)
have called for sustained economic growth to solve the problems
arising from the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and representatives from workers' and
employers' organizations attending the meeting emphasized that
social problems resulting from the financial crisis could only be
solved "in the context of sustained economic growth."
</P>
<P>
The meeting called for renewed efforts to set up appropriate
regulations of financial systems and improve corporate governance
and the functioning of markets.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed the need to respect basic international
labor standards, prevent any possible discrimination against
vulnerable groups such as migrant workers and women, and put an
end to child labor, according to a statement issued Sunday by the
ILO at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the financial crisis in East and
Southeast Asia, which came "totally unanticipated" following
decades of high economic growth, has led to a "swift and
substantial" rise in unemployment, underemployment and poverty.
</P>
<P>
The statement called for a strengthening of the capacity of
governments to "monitor" the employment implications of overall
economic policies, and an "upgrading" of the educational and skill
levels of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also urged the introduction of unemployment
insurance schemes, protection of workers' wages and severance pay,
and a broadening of social systems to help informal workers in
urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by representatives from China,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, South Korea, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
