<HEADLINE> U.S. Co's Herbal Research in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Shaman Pharmaceuticals Inc, a
U.S. company, has been conducting research in traditional herbal
medicines in Uganda without approval from the government, The New
Vision reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Initially the research has been centered on a herb called by
locals as "sukaali" used by local herbalists in fighting against
diabetes. But later, the research has been extended to other
diseases and other aspects of science.
</P>
<P>
Robert Ssebunnya, the Health Minister of Buganda Kingdom, a
traditional region in the center of the African nation, told the
paper that a solution extracted from local herbs fighting against
AIDS and a solution believed to be water hyacinth killer have
been sent to Maurice Iwu, a Nigerian herbalist serving for Walter
Reed Army Institute of Research in Baltimore, Maryland of the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
Iwu has already succeeded in converting the anti-hyacinth
herbal solution into powder form, the health official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
