<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Talks a Meaningful Start to Peace: Pakistan FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan Sunday described the on-going intra-Afghan talks
in Islamabad as a "meaningful start" towards the restoration of
durable peace in that war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's Taliban militia and the rival Northern Alliance
Sunday entered into their first formal face-to-face meeting in
more than a year, with an aim to negotiate an early end to the
20-year-old Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
"It is a great day in the history of Afghanistan" as the
warring factions are holding talks on the solution of the
protracted Afghan conflict, Gohar, as the representative of the
host country Pakistan, told the ceremonial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The talks "generated renewed expectations for peace in
Afghanistan," he said, calling on Taliban and alliance delegates
to work seriously for the general good of the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the conflict has brought severe destruction
to Afghanistan and made the young generations grow up knowing only
war.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Pakistan's consistent stance on the Afghan
issue was to seek peace through negotiations under the auspices of
the United Nations and the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC).
</P>
<P>
The Afghan Joint Steering Committee, which is made up of five
delegates from the Taliban and nine from the alliance, is
proceeding to the working session after the ceremonial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee is expected to discuss the establishment
of an Ulema (religious scholar) Commission, ceasefire, exchange of
prisoners of war and provision of humanitarian aid to the Afghans.
</P>
<P>
The talks are being presided over by OIC Assistant Secretary
General Ibrahim Saleh Bakar and Head of the U.N. Special Mission
on Afghanistan, James Ngobi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
