<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Damage in Indonesia Reaches One Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The forest fires which have been
raging in Indonesia's East Kalimantan province since January have
burned some 442,800 hectares of land with losses estimated to
reach 8.270 trillion rupiah (1.06 billion U.S. dollars), official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit are the forest concessionary areas, where almost
253,000 hectares of land were charred with material losses
estimated to reach 5 trillion rupiah (641 million U.S. dollars),
according to data from the province's Natural Disaster Control
Unit, media reports reaching here Sunday said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the National Oceanic Atmospher Administration (NOAA)
satellite data, 13 hot spots were detected in East Kalimantan
forests where deposits of coal are rich.
</P>
<P>
A data officer at the local disaster unit said the satellite
data failed to provide the exact number of hot spots, as some were
covered by clouds or haze when satellite photos were taken.
</P>
<P>
He also said the latest drought index in those areas has
reached 2,000, a number considered close to "dangerous."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reports said, many orangutans have been forced
to seek safer places in nearby settlement areas since forest fires
broke out in the Kutai National Park in East Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
In the past month, the disaster unit has saved dozens of
injured or starving orangutans fleeing the fires in the park, a
provincial official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Many of the around 2,000 orangutans in East Kalimantan are
currently wandering at the settlement areas.
</P>
<P>
"We give them food or treat them if they are sick and later
release them again," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to extinguish the fires -- blamed largely on big
companies and farmers using slash-and-burn methods to clear land
for planting -- have generally been unsuccessful in the
drought-stricken province where little rain has fallen since last
July, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
