<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Workers Monthly Income Exceeds 120 US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The average monthly income of
workers per capita in this capital of south China's Guangdong
Province exceeded 120 US dollars in the first quarter of this
year, up 9.2 percent over a year ago, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's per worker monthly income in the first three months
was the highest among China's ten largest cities.
</P>
<P>
As income grows, Guangzhou residents are spending more on
non-commodity consumption. Residents in Guangzhou spent an average
608 yuan for non-commodity consumption in the first quarter, which
accounted for 24.5 percent of all spending during the period, up
from 22 percent for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also indicate that Guangzhou residents'
spending on health care rocketed 2.5 times in the first three
months. The growth rate for spending on transportation and
telecommunication and on entertainment was up 30.9 and 9.4
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
While demand for major household electric appliances such as
refrigerators, washing machines and color TV has basically
saturated in Guangzhou, high-quality and multi-functional air
conditioners, stereo systems, VCDs and cameras have become new hot
buys, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Despite spending rises, Guangzhou residents' savings deposits
at banks grew 7.4 percent in the first quarter to 165.7 billion
yuan by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou residents also purchased 2.99 billion yuan worth of
state treasury bonds in the first three months, 3.7 times the
corresponding figure of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
