<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sensitive Index on BSE Drops 230 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The sensitive index on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the week dropped 230
points in the wake of heavy bull liquidation and profit-booking by
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index rose to 4,285.57 on Tuesday, but
dropped to 3,954.31 on Friday, before ending the week at 4,049.98
as against the last weekend close of 4,186.76.
</P>
<P>
The national index dropped by 59.41 points to 1,780.64 at the
weekend from the previous weekend close of 1,840.05. The BSE-200
and US dollar index were quoted down at the weekend close at
402.28 and 168.66 compared with last weekend's close of 417.07 and
174.86 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business on BSE was up at 74,608.9 million rupees
(1,937.89 million U.S. dollars) during the week from last week's
turnover of 51,999.4 million rupees (1,350.63 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The downslide on the BSE market was arrested to some extent by
speculation of a likely cut in the Cash Reserve Ratio and the
Statutory Liquidity Ratio in the ensuring credit policy. Finance
Minister Yashwant Sinha's reported opposition to curbing inflation
through a tight monetary policy also found favor with the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
