<HEADLINE> Returning Serb Refugees to be Protected: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Local officials and the United
Nations representatives signed Saturday in Drvar, a town west of
Sarajevo, an agreement to protect the safety of returning ethnic
Serb refugees and local Croat residents.
</P>
<P>
This agreement was their joint reaction to the clash between
the ethnic Serbs and Croats breaking out there on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The clash began when the returning Serb refugees found their
former habitats were still occupied by the Croats since the war.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, security has been strengthened by the
Multinational Stabilization Force and local police.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Klein, U.N. Deputy Representative in Bosnia and
Herzegovina, emphasized that the international community will not
tolerate any attacks on returning refugees, adding that punishment
must be meted out to violators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
