<HEADLINE> Afghan Factions Start Crucial Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia
and the rival Northern Alliance Sunday entered into their first
formal face-to-face meeting in more than a year, with an aim to
negotiate an early end to the protracted conflict ravaging their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Steering Committee, which is made up of five
delegates from the Taliban and nine from the alliance, met here as
scheduled under the auspices of the United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan, OIC Assistant
Secretary General Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, acting head of the U.N.
Afghan peace mission based in Islamabad N. Gobi, and diplomatic
envoys from Afghanistan's six neighboring countries, as well as
those from the U.S. and Russia attended the inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
After holding a ceremonial meeting, the two rival factions
would immediately proceed to working sessions, and they are
expected to first formally adopt the agenda.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the agenda may include the establishment of
an Ulema (religious scholar) Commission, ceasefire, exchange of
prisoners of war and provision of aid to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia control about two thirds of Afghanistan,
including the capital Kabul, and have imposed a strict Islamic
rule on a country gripped by 20 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance, which controls the rest of the country,
consists of the ousted Afghan president Burhannudin Rabbani,
former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood, ethnic Uzbek warlord
Rashid Dostum and a Shiite Muslim faction. 
