<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Closes Down Some Trade Organizations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has closed
down some state-run trade organizations to cut down state
expenditures and promote private trading and economic development,
the New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The shut down bodies under the Ministry of Commerce include
General Merchandise Trading, Medicine and Medical Equipment
Trading, Construction and Electrical Stores Trading, Inspection
and Agency Services, Myanmar Department Stores, Myanmar Import and
Export Services, and Stationery, Printing and Photographic Stores
Trading.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Commerce Colonel Kyaw Shwe told a meeting
here Saturday that the organizations were closed down as they did
not conform to the market-oriented economic system.
</P>
<P>
He also said import and export formalities will be simplified
and the authorities will grant related licenses within 48 hours
for entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Myanmar commerce authorities drew up a
new list of items of goods for import and export as part of its
trade policy.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar exported 880 million
U.S. dollars' worth of goods in 1997, while it imported
commodities valued at 2.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
