<HEADLINE> U.S. First Lady Questioned by Whitewater Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton was questioned by Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr on
Saturday about her legal work while President Bill Clinton was
governor of Arkansas, White House counsel Charles Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the White House, Ruff said Hillary
Clinton was interviewed by independent counsel Starr and his staff
for about five hours at the White House on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said the first lady was under oath for the session, which
was videotaped for presentation to a grand jury in Little Rock,
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
"The subjects, generally, were matters concerning the Rose Law
Firm's legal representation of Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan
and Mrs. Clinton's relationship with related individuals," Ruff
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not say whether the first lady answered all
questions posed to her.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth time Hillary has been questioned in the
Whitewater inquiry since June 1994, including a January 1996
personal appearance before the grand jury. And it is likely to be
the last as the Whitewater grand jury will be dismissed on May 7.
</P>
<P>
Hillary was a partner at the Rose Law Firm and she and her
husband, who was then governor of Arkansas, were business partners
with James and Susan McDougal who were convicted of bank fraud
arising out of financial transactions related to the Whitewater
real estate investment deal.
</P>
<P>
James McDougal died last month in a federal prison in Texas
where he was serving time. Susan McDougal is serving two years in
federal prison on the fraud conviction.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors are trying to determine whether Hillary misled
regulators or tried to conceal documents at her firm about the
nature of her legal work.
</P>
<P>
The first lady has steadfastly denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
