<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Measures Encourages Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Customs announced
new measures recently to promote Pudong's further development and
opening to the world, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The measures will support exports and the reform of State
enterprises, encourage large domestic companies to move into
Shanghai and spur the growth of private firms.
</P>
<P>
Executive Vice-Mayor Chen Liangyu praised the measures as
aids to the rapid growth of the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the new initiative, the Waigaoqiao Free Trade Zone will
enjoy faster development, the paper quoted Shen Yaohua, deputy
director of Shanghai Customs as saying.
</P>
<P>
High-tech enterprises, pillar industries and multinational
corporations can set up centers in the zone to distribute
parts. Maintenance bonded warehouses can also be established, Shen
said.
</P>
<P>
The new measures allow the zone's bonded markets to hold
various international exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
Convenient services will be provided for key projects in Pudong
that will manufacture Buick cars, electronics and electrical
products.
</P>
<P>
A special information network will be created to link the
customs office with grain, oil and metals exchanges, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
All enterprises will be able to access Shanghai Customs'
Electronic Data Interchange network, he said. A new office will
open at the Shanghai Shipping Exchange in the latter part of this
year to service exports.
</P>
<P>
Customs will simplify procedures and approve projects faster
than before, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Preferential treatment will be given to the processing trade
which now makes up 51 percent of the area's total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
High technology, pillar industries and technical projects will
enjoy high priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises involving these sectors will be allowed to set up
bonded warehouses and factories to facilitate their
exports. Customs will give the same treatment to private
enterprises if permitted, Shen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
