<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax System to Broaden Scope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Fees charged by local governments
to fund the development of public facilities are expected to be
brought within the ambit of the taxation system as part of China's
drive to review off-budget levies, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Those fees to be turned into taxes are likely to be charges
applied on an ongoing basis, such as those relating to
environmental protection and social security, the paper quoted
officials with the State Administration of Taxation (SAT) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Fees for specific services provided on demand, such as issuance
of documents, are expected to be retained. Illegal fees will be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Besides local taxes, China's local governments at all levels
collect numerous fees for various purposes.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji last month said China's new government is
determined to stamp out irregular levies and turn some necessary
fees into taxes.
</P>
<P>
SAT vice-director Cheng Faguang said the transition to a market
economy makes it imperative to integrate as many fees as possible
with the taxation system.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform will remove extra burdens imposed on
enterprises and individuals by superfluous charges.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the reform would also improve the efficiency of
China's public finance sector.
</P>
<P>
Many off-budget items are unreasonable. Furthermore, funds
raised in such ways are often used ineffectively and even lead to
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance, the State Administration of Taxation
and the Economic Restructuring Office under the State Council are
working together to prepare a plan for the reform, according to Li
Jianbao, director-general of SAT's tax policy and legislation
department.
</P>
<P>
Their first move will be to conduct a survey to gain a clear
picture of the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The work will be very complicated. We will certainly meet with
obstacles in the reform because it will affect the interests of
certain parties," Cheng said, "But we are confident we will
succeed."
</P>
<P>
SAT officials said the reform may lead to changes concerning
local governments' rights to make decisions on taxation.
</P>
<P>
At present, varieties and rates of local taxes are all
stipulated by the central government, leaving the local government
no room to make adjustments according to local conditions.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they are considering the feasibility of
empowering local governments to make decisions on some local
taxes, including vehicle taxes, land occupation and butchery
taxes, but have not yet reached any conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
