<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Audit Office to Tighten Supervision, Fight Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- State auditors will sharpen their
vigilance over State finances and State property and step up
their fight against corruption, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Auditors will be required not only to check the authenticity of
fiscal income and expenditure claims, but also to make suggestions
and give advice on how to strengthen management and improve
efficiency, the paper quoted newly appointed Auditor General Li
Jinhua as saying.
</P>
<P>
Appointed at the First Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress last month, Li is expected to face a challenging tenure
at the National Audit Office. A fully operational auditing system
suitable for the socialist market economy in China is supposed to
be put in place within the next five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Li said auditors will pay more attention to helping audited
units establish scientific management system, strengthen
supervision and improve the operational efficiency of capital.
</P>
<P>
They will also shift their focus from individual cases to
analysis and research of common problems in order to be able to
offer suggestions to the government policy makers to improve
policies and regulations.
</P>
<P>
He said the finance sector and State enterprises are likely to
bear the brunt of tightened examination.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil that has battered Southeast Asian
countries since last year has highlighted the importance of
financial supervision in averting financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Li said scrutiny of State financial institutions and
non-banking financial institutions such as trust and securities
companies must be tightened.
</P>
<P>
His office will organize a nationwide audit of securities
companies this year, concentrating on four national broking houses
-- China Securities Co, Guotai Securities Co, Southern Securities
Co and Haitong Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
The National Audit Office checked 110 trust companies
nationwide last year and discovered a series of problems including
low quality of assets and high liability ratios, arousing the
concern of top leaders.
</P>
<P>
Famous for his impartiality, Li played a key role in the
investigation of the corruption case involving Chen Xitong, former
Party chief of Beijing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
A graduate of the Central University of Finance and Economics,
55-year-old Li said that in the past 15 years, audit offices
nationwide had helped the country reduce expenditure by a total of
140 billion yuan (16.9 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980426.0158 </DOCNO>
