<HEADLINE> Private Border Trade Growing In Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harbin, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Suifenhe, a border city in
Heilongjiang Province in northeast China, did 1.5 billion yuan
worth of private border trade during the January-March period this
year, and 9.05 million US dollars of the 11.87 million US dollars
worth of exports during the first quarter, came from the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The city reported six billion yuan private trade value last
year and tax income from this field accounted for a third of the
city's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
A provincial government official says that there have been
about 400 Russians in Suifenhe buying goods every day since the
beginning of 1998, and during the Spring Festival, the number went
up to 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Trade fairs in the city have also attracted 4,500 businesses
from other provinces and cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute the growing trade to improved
Sino-Russian relations and quality in Chinese products, and to
preferential policies for traders.
</P>
<P>
Local bazaars have expanded from the garment and agriculture
trade of five years ago to 36 markets in building materials, furs,
and electric appliances with an 80,000-sq m space that now
attracts 15,000 business people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
