<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volkswagen to Improve Bid for Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Volkswagen AG has decided
to make an improved bid for British luxury car manufacturer
Rolls-Royce, said German news reports Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A new offer put forward by Volkswagen chief Ferdinand Piech had
been endorsed by the company's supervisory board at a special
meeting Saturday evening, the German news agency DPA quoted
company sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan, Volkswagen's previous offer of 1.1 billion
marks (611 million U.S. dollars) would be increased significantly.
The exact figure, however, was still unknown, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The new offer would also include pledges to keep the British
management and production site of Rolls-Royce and to boost the
annual output of the British noble brand from the current 2,000 to
about 10,000 units, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen supervisory board reportedly also approved an
alternative plan which foresaw a revival of the company's former
super luxury brands of Horch and Bugutti should the bid for
Rolls-Royce fail.
</P>
<P>
With the new offer, Volkswagen wants to outgun its German rival
BMW which was selected by Rolls-Royce's parent Vickers as the
preferred bidders at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Vickers and BMW are in exclusive negotiations about
the German carmaker's 340 million pound (570 million U.S. dollar)
bid for Rolls-Royce which Vickers reportedly wants to further
improvement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vickers set the exclusive bargaining period for 30
days, which means that after May 1, it will in a position to
consider any improved bids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
